xt <- rnorm(43,5000,10)
t <- 1:43
xts <- xt - 10*t
plot.ts(xts)

  1. The R codes for randomly generating and displaying the plot of a nonstationary daily time series wt from January 2000 to December 2000 whose mean and variance decrease with time. How much bigger is the mean in January compared to the mean in December? How much bigger is the variance in January compared to December?
t <- 1:365
wt <- rnorm(t, 30 - 2*t/36.5, 10 - t/36.5)
plot.ts(wt)

Jan <- wt[1:31]
Dec <- wt[335:365]
meanJan <- mean(Jan)
meanJan
## [1] 29.47258
varJan <- (sd(Jan))^2
varJan
## [1] 88.16614
meanDec <- mean(Dec)
meanDec
## [1] 10.65607
varDec <- (sd(Dec))^2
varDec
## [1] 0.5000634

The mean for January was 18.8165127 bigger than the mean for December. The variance for January was 87.6660776 bigger than in December.

  1. The R codes for randomly generating and displaying the plot of a monthly time series zt from January 2000 to December 2010 with mean and variance both around 100 and with semi-annual seasonality.

zts <- ts(zt + (zt/2)*(abs(sin((t*pi)/6))) , frequency = 12, start = c(2000,1))
plot.ts(zts)
